The '''Hepialidae''' are a family of [[moth]]s with about 500 species recorded worldwide. Most species display strong [[sexual dimorphism]] with the males generally being smaller but more boldly marked than the females. Moths of this family are often referred to as '''swifts''' or '''ghost moths''', as they are [[crepuscular]] and the male in particular of the European [[Ghost Swift]] is white and conspicuous when forming a "[[lek]]" at dusk (Andersson ''et al.'', 1998). 

The family is considered to be primitive with a number of structural differences to other moths including very short [[antennae]] and lack of a [[proboscis]] or [[frenulum]] (see Kristensen, 1999: 61-62 for details).

The [[larva|larvae]] feed in a variety of ways: some feed on the foliage, some feed underground on the [[root]]s and some feed internally in the stem or trunk of their food plants. They more resemble the maggots of [[Diptera]] than other moth or [[butterfly]] larvae. The female does not lay its [[egg (biology)|eggs]] in a specific location but scatters the eggs while in flight (broadcasting), sometimes in huge numbers (over 10,000 from a single female in some species).

== Species ==

The following species are found in [[Europe]]:

*''Gazoryctra fuscoargentea'' - Northern [[Scandinavia]]
*''G. ganna'' - [[Alps]], northern Scandinavia, northern [[Russia]]
*''Hepialus humuli'' [[Ghost Moth]] - Europe
*''Korscheltellus lupulina'' [[Common Swift (moth)|Common Swift]] - Europe
*''Pharmacis aemiliana'' - [[Italy]]
*''P. anselminae'' - Italy
*''P. bertrandi'' - [[France]]
*''P. carna'' - Central and eastern Europe
*''P. castillana'' - [[Spain]]
*''P. claudiae'' - Italy
*''P. fusconebulosa'' [[Map-winged Swift]] - Europe
*''P. pyrenaica'' - [[Pyrenees]]
*''Phymatopus hecta'' [[Gold Swift]] - Central and northern Europe
*''Triodia adriaticus'' - [[Croatia]], [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]], [[Greece]], [[Crete]]
*''T. amasinus'' - [[Balkans]]
*''T. sylvina'' [[Orange Swift]] - Europe

